<activity><title>Changing the Base</title>

<introduction><p>It is useful to express any exponential function with base <m>e</m>. This is easy to do.</p></introduction>  

<task><p>Which law of exponents tells us that <m>~(e^k)^t = e^{kt}~</m>?</p></task>

<task><p>Follow the steps to write <m>P = 25(\alert{10})^t</m> as <m>P = 25 (\alert{e^k})^t</m></p> 
  <p>We need to replace <m>10</m> by <m>e^k</m>. Solve the equation <m>~10 = e^k~</m> for <m>k</m>. Round your answer to tenths.</p>
  <p>Substitute your value for <m>k</m> into the formula for <m>P</m>.</p>
  <p>Check that the two formulas for <m>P</m> give the same outputs for <m>x = 1,~x=2,~</m> and <m>x=3</m>.</p></task>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>It is very helpful to demonstrate that both forms of the function have the same graph.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Rewrite each exponential function with base <m>e</m>:</p>
  <p><ol cols="2">
    <li><p><m>H=12(1.05)^t</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>N=80(0.16)^t</m></p></li>
  </ol></p></task>
</activity>
   
<subsection><title>Check Your Understanding</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Why would you expect the graph of <m>y = \ln {x}</m> to lie between the graphs of <m>y = \log_2 {x}</m> and <m>y = \log_3 {x}</m>?</p></li>
<li><p>What does "ln" stand for in the function <m>y = \ln {x}</m> ?</p></li>
<li><p>Give decimal approximations for the constants <m>\pi</m> and <m>e</m>.</p></li>
</ol></p></subsection>

<subsection><title>Wrap-Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to the natural base:</p>
<p><ul>
<li><p>Graph exponential functions </p></li>   
<li><p>Solve exponential equations</p></li>
<li><p>Convert exponential functions to base <m>e</m></p></li>
</ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>If <m>k</m> is negative in <m>P(t) = P_0 e^{kt}</m>, what does this tell you about the graph?</p></li>
<li><p>To write <m><m>P(t) = P_0 b^t</m> with base <m>e</m>, we set <m>k = \ln b</m>. Why is that?</m></p></li>
<li><p>Why is it easier to solve <m>e^t = 30</m> than <m>2^t = 30</m>?</p></li>
<li><p>Which produces more interest on an investment: annual compounding at rate <m>r</m> or continuous compounding at rate <m>r</m>?</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>

</subsection>

